    "summary": "Mini-retro: design system paid off, repeated approvals were noisy",
    "content": "Mini-retro from Steve Schoger:\n\n**What went well:**\n- The visual design landed cleanly on the first pass. Following the established patterns (token system, BEM naming, flex row layout, empty state styling) meant no blocking visual issues at all. This validates the design system investment -- it made a brand-new page predictable.\n- The pill badge for waiting-on person was a good collaborative refinement. My initial pre-implementation guidance suggested it, Luca's first pass used plain text (which was also reasonable), and Lea's review brought it back. The end result is the right call for scannability.\n\n**What could improve:**\n- Context compaction caused repeated approval requests. I confirmed approval three or four times. Not a huge problem, but it added noise. If there's a way to track approvals more durably (e.g., a task checklist), that would reduce the back-and-forth.\n\n**Process observation:**\n- Pipeline followed. Commit was atomic. No design token changes needed. Good step."
  }
